List of Kent County Cricket Club captains

tables.Name: William South Norton
tables.Notes: No captain is recorded in a match for Kent before 1856 or between the end of the 1870 season and the start of the 1875 season. Norton played for Kent between 1849 and 1870 and was honorary secretary of the county club formed at Maidstone in 1859 until the merger of the two Kent clubs in 1870. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228031.html Other deaths in 1916 - Mr William South Norton] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1917. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Lord Harris
tables.Notes: Harris went on to be an influential administrator of both Kent and MCC . He was appointed captain in 1875 and held the role for 15 years, having been on the committee at the club since 1870. Resigned the captaincy after the 1889 season to take up an appointment as Governor of Bombay , a post he held until 1895. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/233682.html Lord Harris - Obituary] Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1933. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Played his final match for Kent in 1911 aged 60.

tables.Name: Frank Marchant with William Patterson at times
tables.Notes: Marchant was captain for eight seasons between 1890 and 1897. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/229841.html Obituaries in 1946 - Marchant, Mr Francis] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1947. Retrieved 2016-02-27. William Patterson , a solicitor, was often unavailable to play in the first half of the season and was "elected captain" in the second part of four seasons. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155704.html Obituary - William Patterson] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1947. Retrieved 2016-02-27. He captained most frequently in the 1891 and 1892 seasons in which he was captain five times in each August. [https://cricketarchive.com/cgi-bin/player_oracle_reveals_results2.cgi?playernumber=31915&opponentmatch=exact&playername=R&resulttype=All&matchtype=FirstClass&teammatch=exact&startwicket=&homeawaytype=All&opponent=&endwicket=&wicketkeeper=&searchtype=InningsList&endscore=&playermatch=contains&branding=cricketarchive&captain=on&endseason=&startscore=&team=Kent&startseason= WH Patterson as captain in first-class matches where team is Kent] , Player Oracle search result, CricketArchive. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Jack Mason
tables.Notes: Resigned the captaincy after five seasons due to his time commitments as a solicitor. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228436.html Obituaries in 1958 - Mason, Mr John Richard] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1959. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Temporarily captained the side in the last month of the 1909 County Championship winning season when Ted Dillon "stopped playing for business reasons". [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155679.html Edward Dillon - Obituary] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1942. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Cuthbert Burnup
tables.Last: Made 102 consecutive County Championship appearances for Kent between 1899 and the end of his captaincy in 1903. [http://www.kentcricket.co.uk/news/geraint-jones-reaches-impressive-county-championship-milestone Geraint Jones reaches impressive County Championship milestone] , Kent County Cricket Club , 2012-09-03. Retrieved 2016-04-10.

tables.Name: C. H. B. Marsham
tables.Notes: County Championship winners 1906 . Became an England Test selector in 1908. Lewis P (2013) For Kent and Country , pp. 253–256. Brighton: Reveille Press.

tables.Name: Lionel Troughton
tables.Notes: Became Kent's General Manager after 1923. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228178.html Obituaries in 1933 - Troughton, Lieut.-Colonel Lional Holmes Wood] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1934. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Stanley Cornwallis
tables.Notes: A fast bowler who bowled only 560 overs during his three seasons as captain, mainly due to injury. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228583.html Obituaries in 1982 - Cornwallis, The Right Hon. Wykeham Stanley, 2nd Baron] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1983. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: John Evans
tables.Last: Played his only full season whilst captain. Lewis P (2014) For Kent and Country , pp. 165–169. Brighton: Reveille Press.

tables.Name: Geoffrey Legge
tables.Notes: Died in 1940 in a flying accident whilst serving in the Fleet Air Arm . [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/229833.html Legge, Lieut Geoffrey Bevington] , Obituaries during the war, 1940, Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1941. Retrieved 2017-10-27.

tables.Name: Percy Chapman and Bryan Valentine
tables.Notes: Chapman had captained England between 1926 and 1931 before becoming Kent captain. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155476.html Percy Chapman - Obituary] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1962. Retrieved 2016-02-28. He played less regularly from 1936 onwards and the captaincy was shared at various times, with Valentine generally captaining in his absence, although Chapman retained the official club captaincy until the end of the 1936 season and other players were nominated as "deputy captains" in his place. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155419.html Bryan Valentine - Obituary] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1984. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Percy Chapman, Ian Akers-Douglas and Bryan Valentine
tables.Last: Akers-Douglass captained the side five times in 1936. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228425.html Obituaries in 1952 Akers-Douglass, Captain Ian Stanley] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1953. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Ronnie Bryan and Bryan Valentine
tables.Last: Bryan was limited to playing for Kent when not working but was granted a three-month leave of absence in 1937 when he shared the captaincy with Valentine. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228452.html Obituaries in 1970 - Bryan, Ronald Thurston] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1971. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Gerry Chalk
tables.Notes: Killed in action in World War II . Scored over 1,000 runs in both his seasons as captain. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155695.html Frederick Chalk - Obituary] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1945. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Bryan Valentine
tables.Notes: Had previously been joint captain between 1931 and 1937 and had been injured in World War II.

tables.Name: David Clark
tables.Notes: Later became an administrator of Kent, MCC and the ICC . [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/826611.html Obituaries in 2013 - Clark, David Graham] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 2014. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: William Murray-Wood
tables.Notes: Only an occasional player before being appointed as captain in October 1951, having captained the side in the last five matches of the 1951 season. Replaced, against his will, as captain during Canterbury Cricket Week in August 1953 by Doug Wright . Ruygrok P (2017) 'Bill Murray-Wood: the sacked captain' in Kent County Cricket Club Annual 2017 , pp. 233–236. Canterbury: Kent County Cricket Club. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/228446.html Obituaries in 1968 - Murray-Wood, William] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1969. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Doug Wright
tables.Notes: First professional captain. Until this point every captain of the county had been an amateur. Wright replaced William Murray-Wood in August 1953 as captain and was appointed formally after amateur Tony Pawson , the Kent Committee's preferred choice, declined the position.

tables.Name: Colin Cowdrey
tables.Notes: County Championship winners 1970 and Gillette Cup winners 1967 . Longest span as county captain, captaining the county in 250 first-class games over 15 seasons. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155346.html Colin Cowdrey - Obituary] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 2001. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Captained England 27 times between 1959 and 1969 and was the first man to play 100 Test matches . His son, Chris Cowdrey captained the county between 1985 and 1990 and another son, Graham Cowdrey , and grandson Fabian Cowdrey have both played for the county. Mavor A (2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/671071.html The next Cowdrey off the rank] , CricInfo , 2013-09-13. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Mike Denness
tables.Notes: Had stood in as captain when Colin Cowdrey was on England duty [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154509.html Mike Denness - Cricketer of the Year 1975] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 1976. Retrieved 2016-02-28. and took over full-time at the start of the 1972 season. Won six one-day trophies as captain before being replaced as captain and leaving the county at the end of the 1976 season. Pennell M (2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/631231.html Gracious captain; Kent legend] , CricInfo , 2013-04-20. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Denness captained England 19 times and later was chairman and president of Kent. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/736685.html Mike Denness - Obituary] , Wisden Cricketers' Almanack , 2014. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Chris Cowdrey
tables.Notes: Son of Colin Cowdrey , Kent captain from 1957 to 1971. Captained England on one occasion in 1988. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/14919982 Chris Cowdrey on mend after heart attack] , BBC Sport , 2011-09-11. Retrieved 2017-10-27.

tables.Name: Mark Benson
tables.Notes: Benson was injured in 1996 and did not play, retiring in mid-season. He had been appointed captain at the start of the season although Steve Marsh captain the side throughout the season. Ellis C, Pennell M (2010) Trophies and Tribulations , pp. 186–187. London: Greenwich Publishing. 978-0-9564081-0-5 . Later became an umpire, standing in Test matches . Hopps D (2016) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/963787.html Mark Benson - the umpire who made history - calls time on career] , CricInfo , 2016-01-20. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Steve Marsh
tables.Notes: Captained the county to the 1995 National League title when Mark Benson was injured in the latter half of the season. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/100414.html Former Kent Captain Steve Marsh joins PCA Management Ltd] , CricInfo , 2001-01-16. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Took over as club captain at the end of the 1996 season following Benson's retirement.

tables.Name: Matthew Fleming
tables.Notes: Replaced Marsh at the end of the 1998 season, having previously captained the British Army cricket team . [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/77053.html Fleming receives Kent call] , CricInfo , 1998-10-28. Retrieved 2016-02-28. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/kent/2269376.stm County game loses Jazz] , BBC Sport, 2002-09-20. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Was the Chairman of the Professional Cricketers Association from 1998 to 2001 and later became the MCC Chairman of Cricket in 2013 and President in 2016. [https://www.lords.org/news/2016-2/may/matthew-fleming-to-become-next-mcc-president/ Matthew Fleming to be next MCC President] , Lord's, 2016-05-04. Retrieved 2016-05-07. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/1008509.html Matthew Fleming named as new MCC president] , CricInfo , 2016-05-04. Retrieved 2016-05-07.

tables.Name: David Fulton
tables.Notes: Matthew Fleming retained the club captaincy in 2002 with Fulton captaining the side in the County Championship before being appointed sole captain in October 2002. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/97868.html Fleming and Fulton to share Kent captaincy in 2002] , CricInfo , 2001-12-14. Retrieved 2016-02-28. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/122367.html David Fulton to lead Kent in 2003] , CricInfo , 2002-10-25. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Matthew Walker acted as official List A captain for the second half of 2005 after Fulton lost his place in the one-day side. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/kent/4286712.stm Fulton steps down as Kent skipper] , BBC Sport, 2005-09-27. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Fulton stepped down after Kent failed to win the 2005 County Championship.

tables.Name: Robert Key
tables.Notes: Won the Twenty20 Cup in 2007 and the Second Division County Championship title in 2009. [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/320257.html Key reappointed as Kent captain] , CricInfo , 2007-11-14. Retrieved 2016-02-28. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/20393558 Kent: James Tredwell replaces Rob Key as Kent captain] , BBC Sport, 2012-11-19. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Key resigned the captaincy at the end of the 2012 season.

tables.Name: James Tredwell
tables.Last: Resigned after one season to focus on his role within the England team, having missed several matches during 2013 whilst on England duty. [http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/sport/key-replaces-tredwell-as-kent-8793 Rob Key returns to role as Kent Captain as James Tredwell steps down to focus on England career while Sam Northeast is new vice-captain] , Kent Online , 2013-11-13. Retrieved 2016-02-28.

tables.Name: Robert Key
tables.Notes: Previously captain 2006 to 2012. [http://www.kentcricket.co.uk/news/rob-key-re-appointed-captain-for-2015-season Rob Key re-appointed captain for 2015 season] , Kent County Cricket Club, 2015-10-21. Retrieved 2016-02-28. Sam Northeast acted as County Championship captain for much of 2015 and was the one-day captain throughout the year.

tables.Name: Sam Northeast
tables.Notes: Appointed in September 2016 after captaining the team on the field for most of the 2016 season. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/34403264 Sam Northeast: Kent appoint batsman as club captain] , BBC sport website, 2015-09-30. Retrieved 2015-09-30. Reappointed for the 2017 season in September 2016 Hoad A (2016) [http://www.kentonline.co.uk/canterbury/sport/northeast-retains-kent-captaincy-101920/ Kent Cricket confirm Sam Northeast will continue as captain in 2017] , Kent Online , 2016-09-05. Retrieved 2016-09-28. and replaced by the county in January 2018 after declining the offer of a contract extension which would have kept him at Kent beyond the end of the 2018 season. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/42718988 Sam Billings: England limited-overs player replaces Sam Northeast as Kent captain] , BBC Sport , 2018-01-17. Retrieved 2018-01-30. Northeast left Kent to join Hampshire in February 2018, having been given permission to speak to other counties. Tennant I (2018) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22475518/sam-northeast-signs-hampshire Sam Northeast signs for Hampshire] , CricInfo, 2018-02-17. Retrieved 2018-02-20. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/43104848 Sam Northeast: Hampshire sign Kent batsman on a four-year contract] , BBC Sport, 2018-02-19. Retrieved 2018-02-20. Fordham J (2018) [http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/sport/northeast-signs-for-hampshire-160346/ Sam Northeast signs for Hampshire on four-year contract] , Kent Online , 2018-02-19. Retrieved 2018-02-20.

tables.Name: Sam Billings
tables.Notes: Appointed in January 2018. Led the club to promotion to Division One of the County Championship in September 2018 alongside a One Day Cup final appearance the same year, and captained the side to the 2021 T20 Blast title. Kent also won the [[2022 One-Day Cup]] competition whilst Billings was club captain, although he did not play in the campaign. [https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/45581431 Kent promoted after thrashing Glamorgan] , BBC Sport , 2018-09-20. Retrieved 2023-10-13. Scott G (2021) [https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/58609102 Kent beat Somerset to win T20 Blast] , BBC Sport , 2021-09-18. Retrieved 2023-10-13. A variety of players captained the side when Billings was playing in Twenty20 leagues or for England sides. Fordham J [http://www.kentonline.co.uk/canterbury/sport/denly-speaks-about-his-hundred-against-pakistan-182370/ Joe Denly speaks about his unbeaten hundred against Pakistan] , Kent Online , 2018-05-03. Retrieved 2018-06-02. Baynes V (2019) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26296513/heino-kuhn-stand-kent-captain-absence-sam-billings-joe-denly Heino Kuhn to stand in as Kent captain in absence of Sam Billings and Joe Denly] , CricInfo , 2019-03-18. Retrieved 2019-03-24. Following a run of disappointing performances at the start of the 2023 season, Billings decided to step down as captain for County Championship matches, but retained the role in other formats. Jack Leaning captained the side in the remaining Championship matches, and at the end of the season Billings resigned the club captaincy. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/67016589 Sam Billings: Kent captain steps down after six years in role] , BBC Sport , 2023-10-05. Retrieved 2023-10-12.

tables.Comments: Two time 1st Team All-American at Midfield. Key contributor on two UVA national title teams, 2019 and 2021 . UVA's all-time career point and goal leader by a midfielder. Prep All American at The Haverford School and key contributor to Haverford School's 2015 #1 ranked team.

Two-time 1st team All American, led Penn State to their first NCAA Semifinals in 2019 . Won Attackman of the Year award in 2019 . Set Division I single season record for Assists in a Season . Prep All American at Haverford School and key contributor to Haverford School's 2015 #1 ranked team.

Long time Swarthmore and University of Pennsylvania coach. Coached Swarthmore 1953 squad to USILA Class "B" National title . Father and son Blake Sr. and Avery Blake Jr. are both in National Lacrosse Hall of Fame.

Two time 1st team All American at midfield and attack, first 4-time lacrosse All-American from Pennsylvania. Avery Blake Sr., long-time coach at Swarthmore and Penn, as well as Blake Jr. are both in National Lacrosse Hall of Fame.

Two time All-American at attack. Key contributor on 2003 Hopkins' finals team . Won national title in 2005 with Johns Hopkins . Among Hopkins' all-time leading scorers. Prep All American at The Haverford School .

Three time 1st team All-American at attack. Key contributor on two straight 1994 and 1995 Salisbury championship teams . Prep All American at Tatnall School . Long time All-Pro with the Philadelphia Wings.
1st team All-American at attack. Key contributor on the 2004, 2005 and 2007 Salisbury championship teams . Prep All American at Penncrest High School . Assistant coached at Swarthmore.
3 time All American at University of Delaware . Led Delaware to Championships in 1981, 1982, and 1983. Prep star at Penncrest High School .
2 time All-American attackman. Key contributor to the 2003 Virginia national title and 2005 Final Four teams. Prep All American at Lower Merion. Long time coach at De La Salle .
All-American midfielder and key contributor to 2007 Johns Hopkins national title team. Prep All-American at Springfield High School .
3 time 1st team All-American defenseman. Led UVA to 3 straight national semi-finals. Prep All American at The Hill School .
Key All-American midfielder on two UVA national title teams, 2019 and 2021 . Prep All American at Strath Haven High School .
1st team All-American defenseman playing under Willie Scroggs, helped develop UNC lacrosse into national power. UNC's first ever 1st team Division I All-American. Prep star at The Hill School.
Two-time 1st team All-American and two-time NCAA Goaltender of the Year . Named 1995 NCAA Championship Outstanding Player leading Terps to finals. Prep All American at Episcopal Academy.

3 time All-American, 2 time 1st team All American, key to defensive unit that led Hopkins to two NCAA Quarterfinals in 2011 and 2012 . Prep All American at La Salle College High School. Named All-World defenseman at the 2014 World Lacrosse Championship , two-time NCAA Defenseman of the Year .

2 time All-American, key to defensive unit that led Hopkins to NCAA Finals in 1972 and 1973 under legendary coach Bob Scott . Prep All American at Lower Merion, one of the first PA Prep stars to play on top tier college lacrosse program.

All-American attackman, led nation in scoring in his senior season with 98 points in 12 games. Among NCAA Division I all-time leading scorers , 1st all-time in single season points-per-game. Prep star at Springfield High School.

3 time All-American led the Nittany Lions in scoring in each of her four years (1979-1982), with two USWLA national championships . Holds Penn State record for goals scored in a game (14). Ranks second in career points (334) and career goals (265) for PSU. Three sport prep star at Penncrest High School .

1st team All-American midfielder. Prep All-American at Episcopal Academy . Key player on 1988 Penn Final Four team. Key contributor to Philadelphia Wings from 1990 to 1999, including four NLL championship.
2 time All American, 1st team All American in 1985. Led Temple to Championship in 1984. Prep star at Lansdowne-Aldan High School .
Key contributor to 3 straight national semifinal teams and captain of the 2011 Virginia national title team. Prep All-American at The Haverford School.

All- American attack and longtime lacrosse official. All-time leader in [http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/LAX_Records/2021/MCollegiate.pdf NCAA lacrosse points-per-game] . From 1975 to 1977 averaged 7.9 points per game, which is 1st all time in Division II.
2 time All-American Defenseman on 1996 , 1997 and 1998 national title teams. Prep All-American at Episcopal Academy.
All-Ivy midfielder on 1994 and 1996 national title teams. Overtime assist to Kevin Lowe in 1994 finals gave Princeton the title. Prep All-American at Episcopal Academy.

3 time 1st team All-American attack including Division III Jack Turnbull Award winner in 1997. Sixth all-time in Division III scoring with 225 goals 96 assists and 321 points. Prep All American at Marple Newtown High School .
2 time 1st team All-American midfielder on three national semifinal teams. Prep All-American at Ridley High School . Professional player for the Philadelphia Wings and Chicago Machine .

1st team All-American goalie, Ensign C. Markland Kelly, Jr. Award winner on 2007 regular season undefeated Big Red squad. Prep star at Episcopal Academy. Professional player with Long Island Lizards .

3 time 1st team All-American attack including Division III Player of the Year in 1990 and 1991. Led Hobart to four straight Division III National Titles . Among all-time Division III scorers with 318 points (173g, 145a). Prep star at Episcopal Academy. Miller was inducted into the National Lacrosse Hall of Fame in 2013.

3 time All-American at attack. Key contributor on two national title teams, 2019 and 2021 . Among all-time leading Division I scorers with over 270 career points. Prep star at Garnett Valley for Frank Urso .

1st and 2nd team All American defenseman at Hofstra. Won two straight state titles at Ridley. Defensive anchor for 2006 Quarterfinal team . Professional player with Philadelphia Wings and Philadelphia Barrage.

Hall of Fame player at Temple and coach at Yale and Florida. 1988 NCAA Player of the Year, led Temple to perfect 19–0 record and NCAA Women's Lacrosse Championship . Spring-Ford High School prep star and All-American in both lacrosse and field hockey at Temple.
All-ACC midfielder at Duke. Two-time All American at Penn Charter where he won a PA state title. 9-11 Attack Casualty . Elected to PA Lacrosse Hall of Fame.
Four time All American, 1st team All American in 2017. Key contributor to 2016 UNC national title team. Prep All-American at Abington High School.
All-American defenseman, earned Bucknell's Lee "Bud" Ranck Award. Second nationally with 38 caused turnovers in 2014.  Prep All-American at Episcopal Academy. Led Ohio Machine to MLL Finals in 2016.

2nd Team All-American midfielder for UMBC and All-American at Ohio State. Junior College All-American at Howard (Md.) Community. Prep All- American at Seneca Valley High School , where Poillon and his father started up the varsity lacrosse program. Poillon scored 410 career goals at Seneca.

Two time All-American , 1st team All American attack in 2017. Led Terps to three straight NCAA finals including 2017 title . Among all-time Terps leader in scoring with 257 points. Three-time Prep All- American at LaSalle College High School .

Defenseman at Robert Morris, All-NEC Rookie pick in 2011 and an NEC Second Team pick in 2014. Rankel amassed 96 ground balls, 60 caused turnovers, 3 goals and 7 assists. Member of NEC All-Academic Team all 4 years.

Two time All-American defenseman at Yale, long time coach at National Lacrosse League and Major Lacrosse League levels. Won three NLL titles as player with Wings. Prep star at Penn Charter. Selected to NLL Hall of Fame and National Lacrosse Hall of Fame.
All-American attack at Princeton and Prep All American at Lower Merion. In top twenty all time Princeton scoring. Won two state titles at Lower Merion.
Three time All-American attackman, 1st all-time in UNC scoring and key contributor to several UNC NCAA Tournament teams . Prep All American at Penn Charter.

1st team All-American at attack and a key contributor to four straight NCAA final Hopkins teams, including the 1984 National Championship team. Among the all-time Leading Scorers at Johns Hopkins . Prep All-American at Harriton High School and Avon Old Farms . Played professionally for the Philadelphia Wings .
4 time All-American, 2 time 1st team All American. Finished career second all time in NCAA Division I points with 383. Led Duke to the 2021 NCAA Final Four . Prep All American at Upper Dublin.
Key contributor at midfield to two straight NCAA national title teams including 1981 and 1982 National Champions . Prep star at Harriton High School.

3 time All-American including 1st team All American at Georgetown, led Georgetown to 3 NCAA quarterfinal appearances, 2-time ECAC Defensive Player of the Year. Played on 2006 and 2010 U.S. Men’s national teams winning gold medal in 2010, named to All-World team. Prep All American at Springfield High School . Sweeney was inducted into the National Lacrosse Hall of Fame in 2023.

Long time Penn State coach. Won two national titles in 1970 and 1972 as head coach of UVA. Among the all-time leaders in college coaching victories with over 300 wins. Prepped at State College High School (PA). Starting midfielder at Penn State playing for his Hall of Fame father, Nick Thiel.

Hall of Fame player under Roy Simmons Sr., long time head coach at Penn State. Was an assistant coach at Syracuse under Roy Simmons Sr. Coached 22 years at Penn State. Son Glenn, also a long time head coach at Penn State.

Prep and college star at Haverford High and West Chester. Coached Maryland to seven NCAA Championships and an NCAA record 50 straight wins in the 1990s and 2000s. All-time leader in career coaching wins with a record of 349 wins and 90 losses at Maryland, Northwestern and Navy.

All-American midfield and key contributor to 1994 NCAA finals team . Prep All American at Conestoga High School . Professional with the Philadelphia Wings, Boston Cannons , Long Island Lizards , New Jersey Pride . Member of 1998 USA Men's World Championship Team .

All American midfielder scored go-ahead goal, also won overtime faceoff converted by Andy Moe into title-winning goal in 1992 National Championship game , won by Princeton in two overtimes. Prep star at West Chester East High School .

Three time All American including 1st Team AA in 2022 at faceoff. Key to two straight Maryland national final teams as well as undefeated 2022 National Title team , Terps were 33 and 1 over that 2021-2022 two year period. Prep All American at West Chester Henderson .
2 time All-American attack, 20th all-time in goals scored at Hopkins and contributor to 2008 NCAA Hopkins finals team . Prep All American at The Haverford School.

Four-time All-American at attack. Led Duke to two straight national championships, 2013 and 2014 . Among all-time leaders in Division I career scoring with 304 points. Prep All American at Lower Merion .
Only undefeated Bucknell lacrosse team, won the Patriot league title in 1996 with wins over Penn, Army and Navy. Controversially, was not selected for the 1996 NCAA Tournament .
No. 7 ranked team in 2011, won the Patriot league title. Led Virginia in 1st round of 2011 NCAA Tournament 10–6, losing game to eventual National Champion 13–12 in overtime.
Won the 2019 NCAA Division III tournament , defeating Amherst 16–12 with the finals played in Philadelphia at Lincoln Financial Field . First PA men's team to win a Division III lacrosse title.
First Drexel lacrosse team to make an NCAA Tournament , defeated #4 seed Penn 16 to 11 in the 1st Round at Franklin Field, advancing to their only quarterfinals appearance.
2009 Division III National Finalist . Lost finals to Cortland State 9–7. Bullets made Division III finals three times during the 2000s.
Won school's 1st Patriot league title in lacrosse. No. 7 seed in 2012 NCAAs . Ranked 4th in nation. Lost to National Title runner-up Maryland in 1st round 10–9 with 7 seconds remaining in game.
Won the 2011 NCAA Division II tournament . 1st PA men's team to win Division II lacrosse title. Also 1st PA men's team to win a national lacrosse title of any kind since 1959.

1st PA based Division I team to reach NCAA Final Four. Led by coach Tony Seaman, Chris Flynn was named NCAA 1st team. In 1988 NCAA tournament , lost to Gary Gait led Syracuse team 11–10 in national semifinals, with Gait making the famous "Air Gait" jump shot from behind Penn's goal.
2008 Women's NCAA Division I tournament finalist, losing to Northwestern 10–6. Won Ivy league title, defeated number one Northwestern during the regular season.
Won 3 national collegiate (USWLA) championships in 1978, 1979 and 1980, defeating Maryland, Massachusetts and Maryland, with a 3-year total record of 45-1-3 under head coach Gillian Rattray.
Won the 1987 Women's NCAA Division I tournament with a record of 17–2, defeated Temple in title game 7–6, led by leading scorer Amanda Veal.
Won the 1989 Women's NCAA Division I tournament with a record of 19–1, defeated Harvard in title game 7–6, led by 1990 NCAA Player of the Year Diane Whipple .

Seeded No. 1 in the 2019 NCAA tournament , first ever Pennsylvania team to get the number one NCAA seeding in Men's lacrosse, second Pennsylvania based college to make men's lacrosse Division I Final Four.

Number 5 seed in the 2023 NCAA tournament , second Penn State team to make NCAA Final Four, lost semi-finals to Duke one minute into 1st overtime on a controversial in the crease play which ultimately resulted in NCAA rules changes.

One of the top teams during pre-NCAA season 1953. Led by National Lacrosse Hall of Famer Avery Blake Jr. , one of the top all-time assist men Orville Wright and National Lacrosse Hall of Fame coach Avery Blake Sr. , Swarthmore's lone loss that season was a 14–13 defeat to Johns Hopkins.
Won the 1988 Women's NCAA Division I tournament going undefeated, defeating  Penn State 15–7, led by National Lacrosse Hall of Famer Amanda O'Leary . O'Leary also won NCAA Player of the Year.
